class Circle:
    def __init__(self, r):
        self.r = r
    @property
    def area(self):
        return 3.14159 * self.r ** 2

c = Circle(2)
print(round(c.area, 2))
c.r = 3
print(round(c.area, 2))
c.area = 100

answer.text:
@property turns a method into a **computed attribute**: you read c.area with no parentheses and the method runs behind the scenes. Change r and the next read recomputes, nothing cached, nothing stale.

Assignment fails because a bare property is read-only; allowing writes takes a separate @area.setter.

The design win: attributes and computations look identical from outside, so you can start with a plain attribute today and swap in logic tomorrow without breaking a single caller. Getter/setter method pairs from Java are unidiomatic here.
